---
import PageShell from '../../../../components/PageShell.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'overview', text: 'Overview', level: 2 },
  { id: 'healthcare-system', text: 'Healthcare System', level: 2 },
  { id: 'residency-requirements', text: 'Moving to Puerto Rico', level: 2 },
  { id: 'insurance-requirements', text: 'Insurance Requirements', level: 2 },
  { id: 'recommended-providers', text: 'Recommended Providers', level: 2 },
  { id: 'costs', text: 'Expected Costs', level: 2 },
  { id: 'scenarios', text: 'Real-World Scenarios', level: 2 },
  { id: 'faqs', text: 'Common Questions', level: 2 },
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { title: 'Puerto Rico Insurance Guide', href: '/countries/puerto-rico/insurance' },
  { title: 'Insurance for Seniors', href: '/insurance-for/seniors' },
  { title: 'USA for Seniors', href: '/insurance-for/seniors/in/usa' },
  { title: 'Bahamas for Seniors', href: '/insurance-for/seniors/in/bahamas' },
  { title: 'Dominican Republic for Seniors', href: '/insurance-for/seniors/in/dominican-republic' },
];

const providerColumns = [
  { key: 'provider', header: 'Provider' },
  { key: 'entryAge', header: 'Max Entry Age' },
  { key: 'renewal', header: 'Renewal' },
  { key: 'monthlyFrom', header: 'From (65-69)' },
  { key: 'prFit', header: 'Puerto Rico Fit' },
];

const providerRows = [
  { provider: 'Medicare Advantage', entryAge: '65+', renewal: 'Lifetime', monthlyFrom: '$0-150/mo', prFit: 'Excellent' },
  { provider: 'Traditional Medicare + Medigap', entryAge: '65+', renewal: 'Lifetime', monthlyFrom: '$174+150/mo', prFit: 'Excellent' },
  { provider: 'Triple-S (Local)', entryAge: 'No limit', renewal: 'Lifetime', monthlyFrom: '$200-400/mo', prFit: 'Local Leader' },
  { provider: 'Humana Puerto Rico', entryAge: 'No limit', renewal: 'Lifetime', monthlyFrom: '$0-100/mo', prFit: 'MA Option' },
  { provider: 'Cigna Global', entryAge: '74', renewal: 'Lifetime', monthlyFrom: '$490-700/mo', prFit: 'For Travel' },
];

const costColumns = [
  { key: 'category', header: 'Expense' },
  { key: 'monthly', header: 'Monthly' },
  { key: 'annual', header: 'Annual' },
];

const costRows = [
  { category: 'Medicare Advantage (65+)', monthly: '$0-150', annual: '$0-1,800' },
  { category: 'Medicare + Medigap', monthly: '$174 + $100-300', annual: '$3,300-5,700' },
  { category: 'Triple-S Plans', monthly: '$200-500/mo', annual: '$2,400-6,000' },
  { category: 'Hospital Stay (with Medicare)', monthly: 'Covered', annual: 'Copays apply' },
  { category: 'Supplemental Coverage', monthly: '$50-200/mo', annual: '$600-2,400' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="Health Insurance for Seniors in Puerto Rico 2026 | Retirement Guide"
  description="Guide to health insurance for seniors retiring in Puerto Rico. US territory, Medicare coverage, Caribbean living, and coverage for Americans 65+."
  headline="Health Insurance for Seniors in Puerto Rico"
  subheadline="Puerto Rico offers Caribbean living with US benefits—Medicare coverage, no passport needed, US citizenship, and tax advantages—a unique retirement destination for Americans."
  heroImage="/images/countries/puerto-rico-hero-bg.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Compare Medicare Options →"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/cigna-global"
>
  <h2 id="overview">Why Seniors Choose Puerto Rico</h2>
  <p>
    Puerto Rico offers Caribbean living with US benefits—Medicare coverage, Social Security, no passport required, and significant tax advantages under Acts 60/20/22. For American retirees wanting Caribbean lifestyle without leaving US jurisdiction, Puerto Rico is uniquely positioned.
  </p>

  <p>
    San Juan has capital amenities, hospitals, and urban living. Condado/Isla Verde offer beach lifestyle near city. Rincon attracts surf community on west coast. Dorado has resort-style retirement. Vieques and Culebra offer island-within-island living. Each area has distinct character.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-3">Key Facts for Seniors</h3>
    <ul class="text-primary-800 space-y-2">
      <li><strong>Healthcare:</strong> Medicare accepted; good hospitals</li>
      <li><strong>Language:</strong> Spanish and English; English common in expat areas</li>
      <li><strong>Cost of Living:</strong> $2,500-5,000/month; lower than mainland</li>
      <li><strong>Climate:</strong> Tropical; warm year-round; hurricane zone</li>
      <li><strong>Legal Status:</strong> US territory; no visa needed for Americans</li>
      <li><strong>Tax Benefits:</strong> Act 60 provides significant tax advantages</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <h2 id="healthcare-system">Puerto Rico Healthcare System</h2>
  <p>
    Puerto Rico healthcare uses US systems—Medicare is accepted, major insurers operate, and hospital quality is good. Centro Medico in San Juan is the main teaching hospital. Hospital HIMA, Auxilio Mutuo, and Ashford Presbyterian provide private care. Many doctors trained in US mainland.
  </p>

  <p>
    Medicare works in Puerto Rico as it does on mainland. Medicare Advantage plans are popular and often include extras. Some specialists may require mainland travel. Overall, healthcare infrastructure is solid—a major advantage over other Caribbean options.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-4 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-2">Medicare in Puerto Rico</h3>
    <p class="text-amber-800 mb-0">
      Medicare works fully in Puerto Rico—both Traditional and Medicare Advantage. Many MA plans offer $0 premiums with excellent benefits. Choose PR-specific plans for local network optimization. Medicare is the key healthcare advantage of Puerto Rico retirement.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="residency-requirements">Moving to Puerto Rico</h2>
  <p>
    No visa needed for US citizens:
  </p>

  <h3>US Citizens</h3>
  <p>
    Simply move—no immigration process. Establish residency for tax benefits (183 days/year). Register for PR tax status. US citizenship means full rights.
  </p>

  <h3>Tax Benefits (Act 60)</h3>
  <p>
    Act 60 offers significant tax advantages for new residents—0% capital gains, reduced income tax on export services. Must become bona fide resident. Consult tax professional for eligibility.
  </p>

  <h3>Non-US Citizens</h3>
  <p>
    Same immigration rules as mainland US. Need visa or green card. Puerto Rico is US territory for immigration purposes.
  </p>

  <h3>Residency Requirements</h3>
  <p>
    For tax benefits: 183+ days/year in PR, closer connection to PR than mainland, tax home in PR.
  </p>

  <h2 id="insurance-requirements">Insurance Requirements</h2>
  <p>
    Insurance options in Puerto Rico:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Medicare:</strong> Full coverage for 65+ (same as mainland)</li>
    <li><strong>Medicare Advantage:</strong> Popular; many $0 premium plans</li>
    <li><strong>Medigap:</strong> Available to supplement Traditional Medicare</li>
    <li><strong>Local plans:</strong> Triple-S, MMM for additional coverage</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-blue-900 mb-2">Insurance Strategy for Puerto Rico</h3>
    <p class="text-blue-800 mb-0">
      Medicare provides excellent base—Medicare Advantage plans in PR often exceptional value with low premiums. Consider mainland travel coverage if you'll visit frequently. Triple-S is local leader. For under-65, look at Triple-S or mainland plans that cover PR.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="recommended-providers">Recommended Insurance Providers</h2>
  <p>
    For seniors in Puerto Rico, Medicare-based options dominate:
  </p>

  <ComparisonTable columns={providerColumns} rows={providerRows} />

  <h3>Why These Options Work for Puerto Rico</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Medicare Advantage:</strong> $0-150/month; comprehensive coverage</li>
    <li><strong>Triple-S:</strong> Local leader; strong PR network</li>
    <li><strong>Traditional Medicare + Medigap:</strong> Flexibility for mainland travel</li>
    <li><strong>Humana:</strong> Strong MA presence in Puerto Rico</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-8">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Get Personalized Senior Quotes</h3>
    <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-4">Compare Medicare options for Puerto Rico.</p>
    <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-3">
      <a href="/go/cigna-global" class="inline-block px-5 py-2.5 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-lg hover:bg-primary-700 transition-colors font-medium" style="color: white !important;">Compare Medicare Plans</a>
      <a href="/go/bupa-global" class="inline-block px-5 py-2.5 bg-neutral-700 text-white rounded-lg hover:bg-neutral-800 transition-colors font-medium" style="color: white !important;">International Options</a>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2 id="costs">Expected Insurance Costs</h2>
  <p>
    Insurance costs in Puerto Rico (US dollars):
  </p>

  <ComparisonTable columns={costColumns} rows={costRows} />

  <h3>Cost-Saving Strategies</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Medicare Advantage:</strong> Many $0 premium plans with excellent benefits</li>
    <li><strong>Local networks:</strong> Choose PR-focused plans for best coverage</li>
    <li><strong>Generic drugs:</strong> Part D plans with low drug costs</li>
    <li><strong>Preventive care:</strong> All Medicare plans cover preventive services free</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="scenarios">Real-World Scenarios</h2>

  <div class="space-y-6 my-8">
    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Scenario 1: Florida Retiree, 68</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-2"><strong>Situation:</strong> $4,000/month Social Security + pension. Moving from Florida. Condado.</p>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-2"><strong>Solution:</strong> Medicare Advantage through Triple-S. Act 60 for investment income.</p>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0"><strong>Cost:</strong> ~$0-50/month Medicare. Caribbean living; tax savings; full Medicare.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Scenario 2: New York Snowbird, 72</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-2"><strong>Situation:</strong> $5,500/month income. Split time PR/NY. Dorado.</p>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-2"><strong>Solution:</strong> Traditional Medicare + Medigap for both locations.</p>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0"><strong>Cost:</strong> ~$325/month for portable coverage. Best of both worlds.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Scenario 3: Returning Puerto Rican, 66</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-2"><strong>Situation:</strong> $3,000/month pension. Born in PR, returning. Rincon.</p>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-2"><strong>Solution:</strong> Medicare Advantage through Humana PR. Local network.</p>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0"><strong>Cost:</strong> ~$0/month premium. Coming home; excellent coverage.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2 id="faqs">Common Questions</h2>

  <div class="space-y-6 my-8">
    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Does Medicare work in Puerto Rico?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
        Yes—Medicare works exactly as on mainland. Part A, B, C (Advantage), D all available. Many providers accept Medicare. Hospitals, doctors, pharmacies participate. Major healthcare advantage of PR over other Caribbean islands.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What about hurricanes?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
        Puerto Rico is in hurricane zone—Maria (2017) and Fiona (2022) caused significant damage. Infrastructure has been rebuilt but vulnerabilities remain. Consider insurance for property damage; have evacuation plans. Some retirees leave during peak season.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I need to speak Spanish?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
        Helpful but not required in tourist/expat areas—English is widely spoken in San Juan, Condado, Dorado. Rural areas and smaller towns more Spanish-dominant. Healthcare providers often bilingual. Learning Spanish enriches experience.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b border-neutral-200 pb-4">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What are the tax benefits?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-0">
        Act 60 offers significant advantages for new residents—0% capital gains, 4% corporate tax, reduced income tax on export services. Must become bona fide PR resident. Not all income types qualify. Consult tax professional; benefits can be substantial.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-8">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Ready to Compare Options?</h3>
    <p class="text-neutral-600 mb-4">Get quotes for Medicare plans in Puerto Rico.</p>
    <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-3">
      <a href="/go/cigna-global" class="inline-block px-5 py-2.5 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-lg hover:bg-primary-700 transition-colors font-medium" style="color: white !important;">Compare Plans</a>
      <a href="/go/allianz-care" class="inline-block px-5 py-2.5 bg-neutral-700 text-white rounded-lg hover:bg-neutral-800 transition-colors font-medium" style="color: white !important;">International Options</a>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="bg-neutral-50 border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6 mt-8">
    <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600 mb-0">
      <strong>Disclaimer:</strong> This guide is for informational purposes only. Insurance requirements, tax regulations, and healthcare access rules change regularly. Always verify current requirements with relevant authorities and consult with licensed insurance and tax professionals.
    </p>
  </div>
</PageShell>
